const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What does the E24 error code mean on my Bosch dishwasher?",
    a: "E24 is a drain fault — the dishwasher can't empty the tub. In the large majority of E24 calls we handle, the cause is a clogged filter, not a failed drain pump. The filter assembly sits inside the tub, under the lower spray arm — twist counterclockwise and lift to remove. Bosch recommends cleaning it monthly. If you've never cleaned it, that's your E24. Clean the filter and the microfilter beneath it, rinse under running water, reinstall, run a drain cycle. If E24 persists with a clean filter, the drain pump impeller may be jammed by debris or the pump has failed — call us."
  },
  {
    q: "How often should I clean my Bosch dishwasher filter?",
    a: "Monthly. Bosch recommends this in their manuals but it's easy to miss. The filter is inside the tub, under the lower spray arm — twist counterclockwise, lift out the cylindrical filter, then lift the flat mesh microfilter beneath it. Rinse both under hot running water. Three minutes, once a month. In SoCal hard water areas — Orange County, San Fernando Valley, Conejo Valley — we also recommend a monthly citric acid cleaning cycle to prevent scale from accumulating on the heating element, which leads to E09 failures. A citric acid cleaner is about $8. An E09 element replacement is $200+."
